1
00:00:02,401 --> 00:00:04,521
(THUNDER CRASHES AND ROLLS)

2
00:00:14,401 --> 00:00:16,001
Confined again.

3
00:00:17,401 --> 00:00:18,961
I cannot bear it.

4
00:00:20,361 --> 00:00:23,161
The very world itself
seems sick.

5
00:00:26,561 --> 00:00:28,841
A most ungenial summer.

6
00:00:28,961 --> 00:00:31,881
I've never known air as dank
and frigid.

7
00:00:32,921 --> 00:00:34,161
Oh!

8
00:00:34,281 --> 00:00:36,001
Dank and frigid?

9
00:00:36,121 --> 00:00:38,681
Who does that remind me of,
I wonder.

10
00:00:38,801 --> 00:00:40,121
Oh!

11
00:00:41,321 --> 00:00:43,961
Sleep well, sweet boy.

12
00:00:45,921 --> 00:00:49,961
Perhaps Lord Byron or
Dr Polidori would read to us?

13
00:00:51,641 --> 00:00:53,921
What would Miss Clairmont
wish to hear?

14
00:00:54,041 --> 00:00:56,961
Something to awaken
thrilling horror.

15
00:00:58,561 --> 00:01:01,361
Yes, Mrs Shelley.

16
00:01:01,481 --> 00:01:04,001
To make us dread to
look around.

17
00:01:04,121 --> 00:01:06,601
- (THUNDER RUMBLES)
- To curdle the blood

18
00:01:06,721 --> 00:01:09,121
and quicken the beatings
of the heart.

19
00:01:09,241 --> 00:01:10,841
I have just the thing.

20
00:01:10,961 --> 00:01:12,281
Oh...

21
00:01:17,681 --> 00:01:19,521
(EXHALES)

22
00:01:19,641 --> 00:01:23,481
Tales Of The Dead.

23
00:01:23,601 --> 00:01:26,601
(THUNDER CRASHES)

24
00:01:31,161 --> 00:01:33,801
"At midnight, we took a torch
to the chapel "

25
00:01:33,921 --> 00:01:35,561
(THUNDER CRASHES)

26
00:01:35,681 --> 00:01:38,081
"With pallid countenance
and trembling limbs,

27
00:01:38,201 --> 00:01:40,041
"we descended to the vault.

28
00:01:41,601 --> 00:01:45,521
"Hildegarde's leaden coffin
loomed before us.

29
00:01:48,361 --> 00:01:51,681
"The Count was seized
with the sensations of terror. "

30
00:01:51,801 --> 00:01:55,161
(HANDLE RATTLES)

31
00:01:55,281 --> 00:01:58,401
"He opened the coffin
with a stifled cry of dread,

32
00:01:58,521 --> 00:02:00,721
"and inside we saw..."

33
00:02:00,841 --> 00:02:03,561
- (BANGING ON DOOR)
- (WOMEN SHRIEK)

34
00:02:03,681 --> 00:02:07,361
I shall send whoever calls
away, my lord.

35
00:02:07,481 --> 00:02:09,161
No, Fletcher.

36
00:02:09,281 --> 00:02:10,321
What if it is she?

37
00:02:11,561 --> 00:02:14,561
(WHISPERS) Hildegarde,
the death-bride.

38
00:02:14,681 --> 00:02:17,001
If something infernal
is on my doorstep,

39
00:02:17,121 --> 00:02:19,521
I should be the one
to go and greet it.

40
00:02:19,641 --> 00:02:22,081
- Infernal?
- (THUNDER CRASHES)

41
00:02:22,201 --> 00:02:23,481
Surely not?

42
00:02:25,001 --> 00:02:27,201
Who is brave enough
to come and see?

43
00:02:30,081 --> 00:02:32,361
(BANGING ON DOOR)

44
00:02:34,841 --> 00:02:38,041
I'll wager it's Shelley,
amusing himself with a trick.

45
00:02:38,161 --> 00:02:40,721
Shelley is not one for tricks.

46
00:02:40,841 --> 00:02:42,201
(CRASH)

47
00:02:47,281 --> 00:02:50,241
There is nothing to be
afraid of.

48
00:02:50,361 --> 00:02:52,321
(ALL SHRIEK)

49
00:03:28,481 --> 00:03:31,281
Good evening! Not quite
the welcome I was hoping for,

50
00:03:31,401 --> 00:03:33,361
but I'll admit
we've looked better.

51
00:03:33,481 --> 00:03:37,121
It's a pleasure to make
your acquaintances. I'm...

52
00:03:37,241 --> 00:03:40,681
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

53
00:03:40,801 --> 00:03:42,321
Nothing?

54
00:03:43,681 --> 00:03:44,721
Weird.

55
00:03:44,841 --> 00:03:46,481
Might need a blow-dry.

56
00:03:46,601 --> 00:03:48,201
Got a bit caught
in the downpour.

57
00:03:48,321 --> 00:03:50,841
Yes, because it is a truth
universally acknowledged...

58
00:03:50,961 --> 00:03:52,081
Wrong writer!

59
00:03:53,841 --> 00:03:57,121
...that one's driver will park
one's carriage

60
00:03:57,241 --> 00:04:00,721
imprudently too far from
whence one is going.

61
00:04:00,841 --> 00:04:02,401
Can we please just come in?

62
00:04:02,521 --> 00:04:04,681
Before we drown to death.
Please.

63
00:04:06,761 --> 00:04:09,081
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

64
00:04:09,201 --> 00:04:10,561
Ha-ha!

65
00:04:16,921 --> 00:04:18,001
DOCTOR: One hour, tops.

66
00:04:18,121 --> 00:04:19,321
GRAHAM: Plus drying time.

67
00:04:19,441 --> 00:04:21,241
DOCTOR: OK, so there was
a spot of rain

68
00:04:21,361 --> 00:04:23,081
and gale-force winds
and a super-long walk.

69
00:04:23,201 --> 00:04:24,201
But I got us here, didn't I?

70
00:04:24,321 --> 00:04:27,201
And Mary Wollstonecraft Godwin,
soon to be Shelley,

71
00:04:27,321 --> 00:04:28,401
screamed in your face.

72
00:04:28,521 --> 00:04:31,441
Quality historical experience,
that. Gold!

73
00:04:31,561 --> 00:04:35,001
(WHISPERS) On the night
that inspired Frankenstein.

74
00:04:35,121 --> 00:04:38,281
If...you'd be so kind...

75
00:04:38,401 --> 00:04:39,721
Blimey!

76
00:04:39,841 --> 00:04:41,841
Excuse me, Yaz. I was
very clear about the rules.

77
00:04:41,961 --> 00:04:45,001
Nobody mention Frankenstein,
and don't interfere.

78
00:04:45,121 --> 00:04:46,841
And nobody snog Byron.

79
00:04:46,961 --> 00:04:49,921
In, out, soak up the atmos.

80
00:04:50,041 --> 00:04:52,721
Witness some of the most
enlightened minds

81
00:04:52,841 --> 00:04:54,841
of a generation
at the pinnacle,

82
00:04:54,961 --> 00:04:57,481
the absolute zenith
of their creativity...

83
00:05:01,241 --> 00:05:03,841
(ALL SHRIEK)

84
00:05:03,961 --> 00:05:05,561
(SHRIEKING STOPS)

85
00:05:05,681 --> 00:05:07,361
What would you all
care to drink?

86
00:05:07,481 --> 00:05:09,881
CLAIRE: We shall teach them
the dance.

87
00:05:10,001 --> 00:05:11,881
(LIVELY PIANO MUSIC)

88
00:05:18,641 --> 00:05:21,121
(SIGHS) I detest all gossip,
you understand.

89
00:05:21,241 --> 00:05:22,921
Utterly abhor it.

90
00:05:24,081 --> 00:05:25,561
Mary goes by Mrs Shelley...

91
00:05:25,681 --> 00:05:27,721
...except she and Percy
are not married.

92
00:05:27,841 --> 00:05:30,241
It really is quite a scandal.

93
00:05:30,361 --> 00:05:32,481
Lord Byron is separated
from his wife.

94
00:05:32,601 --> 00:05:35,201
The rumours are so disastrous
he cannot return to England.

95
00:05:35,321 --> 00:05:39,001
Now he keeps company
with Mary's stepsister,

96
00:05:39,121 --> 00:05:40,481
Miss Clairmont.

97
00:05:40,601 --> 00:05:43,601
We have an exceptionally strong
attachment.

98
00:05:43,721 --> 00:05:46,161
She scrambled 500 miles
from England

99
00:05:46,281 --> 00:05:47,801
to come and see me here.

100
00:05:47,921 --> 00:05:50,361
Couldn't exactly turn her away.

101
00:05:51,841 --> 00:05:54,321
(GASPS) Please excuse me,
fair lady.

102
00:05:54,441 --> 00:05:57,401
I must poppeth
to the little boys' room.

103
00:05:57,521 --> 00:06:01,041
So...that was marvellous.

104
00:06:01,161 --> 00:06:03,161
(PANTS) Is anyone up for,
I don't know,

105
00:06:03,281 --> 00:06:06,761
I'm spitballing here, how about
writing the most gruesome,

106
00:06:06,881 --> 00:06:09,601
spine-chilling ghost story
of all time?

107
00:06:12,161 --> 00:06:14,001
(SPEAKS SOFTLY IN FRENCH)

108
00:06:15,281 --> 00:06:17,881
(THUNDER CRASHES)

109
00:06:21,401 --> 00:06:23,481
(KEY TURNS IN LOCK)

110
00:06:23,601 --> 00:06:25,721
(WIND WHISTLES)

111
00:06:30,521 --> 00:06:31,801
(SHRIEKS)

112
00:06:31,921 --> 00:06:34,441
DOCTOR: ...you know?
A bit of blood and guts?

113
00:06:34,561 --> 00:06:36,481
Throw in a corpse
for good measure.

114
00:06:36,601 --> 00:06:38,681
Float anyone's boat? Mary?

115
00:06:38,801 --> 00:06:40,801
Or perhaps another quadrille?

116
00:06:40,921 --> 00:06:42,521
- I shall choose the music.
- LORD BYRON: Hear, hear!

117
00:06:42,641 --> 00:06:45,881
Excuse me, Doctor.
You broke a rule.

118
00:06:46,001 --> 00:06:47,081
Next, you'll be snogging Byron.

119
00:06:47,201 --> 00:06:49,321
I was trying to get them
back on track.

120
00:06:49,441 --> 00:06:51,361
Something's wrong here.

121
00:06:51,481 --> 00:06:53,521
This night, June 1816,

122
00:06:53,641 --> 00:06:56,241
Byron challenges Mary Polidori
and Percy Shelley

123
00:06:56,361 --> 00:06:58,641
to come up with a ghost story.
Spot the difference!

124
00:06:58,761 --> 00:07:00,001
You and I shall be partners
for the next dance.

125
00:07:00,121 --> 00:07:01,721
Not much writing going on?

126
00:07:02,841 --> 00:07:04,441
And there's no Shelley.

127
00:07:04,561 --> 00:07:06,561
Bingo! They're a man down.

128
00:07:08,121 --> 00:07:09,481
Why?

129
00:07:12,921 --> 00:07:14,881
(FOOTSTEPS)

130
00:07:15,001 --> 00:07:16,241
- Sorry, love.
- (GASPS)

131
00:07:16,361 --> 00:07:17,561
Oh...

132
00:07:17,681 --> 00:07:19,561
Crikey. A bit lost.

133
00:07:19,681 --> 00:07:21,121
Looking for the lavatory?

134
00:07:21,241 --> 00:07:23,241
C'est diabolique, monsieur!

135
00:07:23,361 --> 00:07:25,001
C'est terrible.

136
00:07:28,081 --> 00:07:29,961
Never mind. I can hold it.

137
00:07:31,281 --> 00:07:33,521
Big house like this - there's
got to be a lav somewhere.

138
00:07:35,081 --> 00:07:37,561
(THUNDER CRASHES)

139
00:08:11,081 --> 00:08:13,361
I'm going round in circles
here.

140
00:08:38,401 --> 00:08:40,201
(GASPS)

141
00:08:41,841 --> 00:08:44,241
It is impolite not to announce
oneself, Miss Khan.

142
00:08:44,361 --> 00:08:46,161
Breaking and entering's worse.

143
00:08:46,281 --> 00:08:49,081
I'm not at fault if Lord Byron
selfishly keeps it locked.

144
00:08:49,201 --> 00:08:51,481
What are you after?

145
00:08:53,681 --> 00:08:54,761
Letters.

146
00:08:56,081 --> 00:08:59,961
If he's written about me, I can
ascertain his true sentiments.

147
00:09:05,441 --> 00:09:07,201
Or...

148
00:09:09,521 --> 00:09:11,241
...you could try asking him.

149
00:09:11,361 --> 00:09:12,841
I have.

150
00:09:12,961 --> 00:09:15,161
His answers only increase
the enigma.

151
00:09:17,441 --> 00:09:19,761
I know someone like that.

152
00:09:21,641 --> 00:09:23,401
Mary reproaches me...

153
00:09:24,481 --> 00:09:27,161
...and says I should find
a more reliable prospect.

154
00:09:28,241 --> 00:09:30,001
Not that she can talk.

155
00:09:31,641 --> 00:09:33,561
Perhaps she's right.

156
00:09:33,681 --> 00:09:35,601
His eye does seem to wander.

157
00:09:38,161 --> 00:09:41,521
This enigmatic person
of yours...

158
00:09:41,641 --> 00:09:44,721
Would you trade them for
reliable and dull?

159
00:09:44,841 --> 00:09:47,321
My person's a bit different.

160
00:09:49,161 --> 00:09:50,721
Did you see that?

161
00:09:51,801 --> 00:09:53,401
What?

162
00:09:57,001 --> 00:09:58,561
Nothing.

163
00:09:58,681 --> 00:10:00,681
Trick of the light.

164
00:10:05,521 --> 00:10:07,921
(SONIC BUZZES)

165
00:10:11,081 --> 00:10:14,121
She walks in beauty,
like the night.

166
00:10:14,241 --> 00:10:17,521
Of cloudless climes
and starry skies.

167
00:10:17,641 --> 00:10:19,121
(SONIC BUZZES)

168
00:10:20,881 --> 00:10:22,161
I'm intensely flattered

169
00:10:22,281 --> 00:10:24,321
you're familiar with my work,
Mrs Doctor.

170
00:10:24,441 --> 00:10:26,241
Just Doctor is fine.

171
00:10:27,241 --> 00:10:29,321
I'm quite into Shelley's stuff
too. He about?

172
00:10:29,441 --> 00:10:31,881
Indisposed, I'm afraid.

173
00:10:33,401 --> 00:10:34,761
He won't be joining us.

174
00:10:35,801 --> 00:10:36,961
May I be candid?

175
00:10:37,081 --> 00:10:38,481
Go for it.

176
00:10:38,601 --> 00:10:40,961
I sent my man out to fetch
your carriage,

177
00:10:41,081 --> 00:10:44,041
but it seems to have
disappeared.

178
00:10:48,841 --> 00:10:50,601
(# Chopsticks)

179
00:10:53,241 --> 00:10:54,961
(NOTES JAR)

180
00:10:59,961 --> 00:11:02,001
Such a jaunty air!

181
00:11:02,121 --> 00:11:04,041
Is it popular in the colonies?

182
00:11:04,161 --> 00:11:05,761
Er...yeah.

183
00:11:05,881 --> 00:11:09,201
My nan taught me but I always
get the keys wrong.

184
00:11:09,321 --> 00:11:12,041
But she always said
there's no reason not to try.

185
00:11:13,401 --> 00:11:14,961
I should practise more.

186
00:11:15,081 --> 00:11:18,001
But I confess,
I prefer to write...

187
00:11:18,121 --> 00:11:19,201
Ah.

188
00:11:19,321 --> 00:11:21,121
...even though my efforts
are weak.

189
00:11:21,241 --> 00:11:23,801
I could never hope to match
the achievements of my parents.

190
00:11:23,921 --> 00:11:25,721
My nan would say stick with it.

191
00:11:26,881 --> 00:11:28,961
MARY: Hmm.

192
00:11:30,321 --> 00:11:33,641
- What's his problem?
- Oh...

193
00:11:33,761 --> 00:11:35,481
Pay Dr Polidori no heed.

194
00:11:35,601 --> 00:11:38,361
He's bad-tempered because
he does not sleep.

195
00:11:38,481 --> 00:11:40,881
He walks at night.

196
00:11:41,001 --> 00:11:42,681
A terrible affliction.

197
00:11:42,801 --> 00:11:46,841
Imagine...never being able to
truly rest.

198
00:11:48,521 --> 00:11:50,001
I'm fully aware
of what you want!

199
00:11:50,121 --> 00:11:51,281
Please reveal all.

200
00:11:51,401 --> 00:11:52,801
My third canto.

201
00:11:55,401 --> 00:11:58,121
Of Childe Harold's Pilgrimage,
my work in progress.

202
00:11:58,241 --> 00:12:01,161
Nah, it goes on a bit,
that one. No offence.

203
00:12:02,761 --> 00:12:05,161
Nice mention of Ada, though.
I'm a big fan of hers.

204
00:12:05,281 --> 00:12:07,321
You know of my daughter?

205
00:12:07,441 --> 00:12:09,441
Will do. Gorgeous brain.

206
00:12:09,561 --> 00:12:11,641
Why are you here?

207
00:12:11,761 --> 00:12:13,761
For a quick visit, supposedly,

208
00:12:13,881 --> 00:12:16,641
but I'm getting this really
weird vibe off your house.

209
00:12:16,761 --> 00:12:17,801
Vibe?

210
00:12:17,921 --> 00:12:19,241
Yeah.

211
00:12:19,361 --> 00:12:21,361
I don't want to worry you,

212
00:12:21,481 --> 00:12:23,721
but I'm sensing
that it's sort of...

213
00:12:23,841 --> 00:12:25,841
...unrelentingly evil.

214
00:12:29,401 --> 00:12:32,481
Ryan, it's like a maze
up there,

215
00:12:32,601 --> 00:12:33,441
and they're a few years shy

216
00:12:33,561 --> 00:12:35,481
- of a toilet.
- Sir?

217
00:12:35,601 --> 00:12:36,921
Oh, blimey!

218
00:12:37,041 --> 00:12:38,721
You've gotta stop doing that.

219
00:12:38,841 --> 00:12:40,401
Splendid.

220
00:12:40,521 --> 00:12:42,121
Very convenient.

221
00:12:42,241 --> 00:12:45,121
Ryan, not a khazi
for love nor money,

222
00:12:45,241 --> 00:12:47,361
and a Frenchwoman who's got
a right hump about something.

223
00:12:47,481 --> 00:12:49,521
Mrs Shelley seems fatigued.

224
00:12:49,641 --> 00:12:51,721
Only of waiting to dance.

225
00:12:51,841 --> 00:12:53,601
You're the one
who looks like death.

226
00:12:53,721 --> 00:12:55,561
- Do you insult my visage, sir?
- You might want to

227
00:12:55,681 --> 00:12:57,801
stop shooting daggers and maybe
take a nap, all right?

228
00:12:57,921 --> 00:12:58,801
I beg your pardon?

229
00:12:58,921 --> 00:13:00,601
He means, perhaps you should
take a rest.

230
00:13:00,721 --> 00:13:02,721
I'm a physician.
I'm in rude health.

231
00:13:02,841 --> 00:13:04,561
Whatever you say, mate.
(CHUCKLES)

232
00:13:04,681 --> 00:13:06,361
Then I say choose, sir!

233
00:13:08,161 --> 00:13:09,801
Sorry.
He does this rather a lot.

234
00:13:09,921 --> 00:13:12,121
- Choose your weapon!
- What?

235
00:13:12,241 --> 00:13:13,521
Isn't it obvious?

236
00:13:13,641 --> 00:13:15,121
He's challenging you to a duel.

237
00:13:15,241 --> 00:13:18,241
Oh... Look, hey, look,
I'm not here to fight anyone,

238
00:13:18,361 --> 00:13:19,561
- so everyone just calm down.
- Fletcher!

239
00:13:19,681 --> 00:13:21,961
- You will be my second.
- (FLETCHER GROANS)

240
00:13:22,081 --> 00:13:24,241
- Will Mr O'Brien be yours?
- No!

241
00:13:24,361 --> 00:13:26,241
- Cheers, mate.
- No, what I mean... No,

242
00:13:26,361 --> 00:13:29,001
because there's going to be no
duel. I absolutely forbid it.

243
00:13:29,121 --> 00:13:32,081
- Ooh! Ooh!
- What's up? What's up?

244
00:13:32,201 --> 00:13:34,561
I shall return with my pistol.

245
00:13:38,641 --> 00:13:40,361
He's getting a gun.
He's getting a gun.

246
00:13:40,481 --> 00:13:41,361
He's getting a gun.

247
00:13:46,321 --> 00:13:48,201
Whatever is that?

248
00:13:48,321 --> 00:13:49,921
No...

249
00:13:50,041 --> 00:13:51,801
I think it's a...

250
00:13:51,921 --> 00:13:54,841
...hand!
It's definitely a hand!

251
00:13:54,961 --> 00:13:56,321
Get it off him.

252
00:13:56,441 --> 00:13:59,161
- Doc!
- It's so strong!

253
00:13:59,281 --> 00:14:00,401
- (GASPS)
- And ferocious!

254
00:14:00,521 --> 00:14:02,281
(MARY GASPS)

255
00:14:04,641 --> 00:14:06,161
Great shot.

256
00:14:13,401 --> 00:14:14,841
Hmm.

257
00:14:14,961 --> 00:14:17,041
14th. No...

258
00:14:17,161 --> 00:14:19,041
15th century. Touch more umami.

259
00:14:19,161 --> 00:14:21,081
- She licked it!
- She is

260
00:14:21,201 --> 00:14:23,521
the most baffling creature
I've ever been acquainted with.

261
00:14:23,641 --> 00:14:27,121
Human. Protein. Collagen and...

262
00:14:27,241 --> 00:14:29,081
...nothing abnormal.

263
00:14:29,201 --> 00:14:31,401
What kind of implement is that?

264
00:14:31,521 --> 00:14:33,361
One that zaps people's
heads off who threaten

265
00:14:33,481 --> 00:14:35,961
- people with guns.
- I don't think they're

266
00:14:36,081 --> 00:14:37,641
- really from the colonies.
- No.

267
00:14:37,761 --> 00:14:41,881
She is from somewhere
much, much stranger.

268
00:14:42,001 --> 00:14:43,761
The north.

269
00:14:43,881 --> 00:14:48,201
How did it come to life, then?
Was it haunted, or something?

270
00:14:48,321 --> 00:14:49,241
Unlikely.

271
00:14:49,361 --> 00:14:52,241
Well, you did say the house
was evil.

272
00:14:52,361 --> 00:14:53,681
Well, that's a development.

273
00:14:53,801 --> 00:14:55,521
I've been getting a vibe.

274
00:14:55,641 --> 00:14:57,841
If there is evil here,
I know who brought it in.

275
00:15:01,321 --> 00:15:05,841
(SIGHS) Very well. I may have
a skeleton...in my chamber.

276
00:15:05,961 --> 00:15:08,761
Right. You keep an eye on
Trigger Happy.

277
00:15:10,681 --> 00:15:12,601
Me and you need to take a squiz
at your skeleton.

278
00:15:12,721 --> 00:15:15,241
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

279
00:15:26,361 --> 00:15:29,281
- It's a collection.
- Of what?

280
00:15:29,401 --> 00:15:31,441
- Dead stuff?
- Relics of war.

281
00:15:31,561 --> 00:15:32,481
(SONIC BUZZES)

282
00:15:32,601 --> 00:15:34,401
From my travels.

283
00:15:34,521 --> 00:15:38,961
Reminders that we tread
on the dust of empires.

284
00:15:39,081 --> 00:15:43,561
Crops now grow
where blood was split.

285
00:15:43,681 --> 00:15:45,201
An innocent fascination,
I assure you.

286
00:15:45,321 --> 00:15:46,561
Waterloo!

287
00:15:46,681 --> 00:15:48,961
Oh! I love a good plume!

288
00:15:50,161 --> 00:15:51,161
What do you think?

289
00:15:51,281 --> 00:15:53,761
A 15th-century soldier...

290
00:15:56,241 --> 00:15:58,241
...from the Battle of Morat.

291
00:16:01,281 --> 00:16:03,801
His final remains.

292
00:16:03,921 --> 00:16:05,361
One hand gone.

293
00:16:05,481 --> 00:16:07,161
Both hands gone.

294
00:16:08,361 --> 00:16:10,361
Great. There's another
on the loose.

295
00:16:10,481 --> 00:16:11,441
Keep your eyes peeled.

296
00:16:11,561 --> 00:16:13,321
Anything else strange happen
since you've been here?

297
00:16:15,641 --> 00:16:19,601
When the weather turned,
Shelley began having visions.

298
00:16:19,721 --> 00:16:20,961
He's prone to them.

299
00:16:22,001 --> 00:16:22,921
What did he see?

300
00:16:23,041 --> 00:16:25,201
An apparition of a figure...

301
00:16:25,321 --> 00:16:27,041
...floating above the lake.

302
00:16:28,281 --> 00:16:31,481
When you said he was
indisposed, what did you mean?

303
00:16:31,601 --> 00:16:34,121
Uh, well,
when he didn't join us,

304
00:16:34,241 --> 00:16:36,721
my mind naturally wandered
to the idea of

305
00:16:36,841 --> 00:16:40,441
some torrid assignation
in town.

306
00:16:40,561 --> 00:16:42,641
Shelley often retires
to our chalet...

307
00:16:42,761 --> 00:16:44,441
...to write.

308
00:16:46,681 --> 00:16:49,441
Maison Chapuis. On the shore.

309
00:16:49,561 --> 00:16:52,241
You should probably pop down
and have a chat.

310
00:16:54,121 --> 00:16:55,801
(SNORING)

311
00:16:55,921 --> 00:16:57,521
(CLOCK TICKS)

312
00:17:04,961 --> 00:17:07,761
You're like ninjas, you lot.
(CHUCKLES)

313
00:17:07,881 --> 00:17:10,201
Fair play to you, though, love.
Food!

314
00:17:10,321 --> 00:17:11,881
There's never any food.

315
00:17:12,001 --> 00:17:14,521
Cheers. You're a better. Yeah.

316
00:17:14,641 --> 00:17:18,081
- Baby-sitting duty. Yeah.
- (SNORING)

317
00:17:18,201 --> 00:17:20,761
He'll be no trouble now,
though. Dead to the world.

318
00:17:20,881 --> 00:17:22,281
This apparition -

319
00:17:22,401 --> 00:17:25,001
did Shelley describe it
in any more detail?

320
00:17:25,121 --> 00:17:27,201
Dark. Charred by fire.

321
00:17:28,481 --> 00:17:30,361
Suspended over the water

322
00:17:30,481 --> 00:17:32,961
like a death god
rising from Hades.

323
00:17:33,081 --> 00:17:34,521
Right...

324
00:17:34,641 --> 00:17:36,281
Nothing too sinister, then.

325
00:17:40,761 --> 00:17:43,961
You can ask him more questions
when we get to the chalet.

326
00:17:47,241 --> 00:17:50,361
Did we just go down to the top?

327
00:17:52,281 --> 00:17:55,121
What reanimates bones
and leaves no trace?

328
00:17:55,241 --> 00:17:56,961
Why just the hands?
Why only parts?

329
00:17:57,081 --> 00:17:59,361
However, my collection's
not demonic?

330
00:17:59,481 --> 00:18:00,401
Correct.

331
00:18:00,521 --> 00:18:02,721
But I'll probably come back
for this, though.

332
00:18:02,841 --> 00:18:05,121
Strictly for, er,
safety purposes.

333
00:18:05,241 --> 00:18:08,161
Not because it really suits me,
or anything.

334
00:18:08,281 --> 00:18:12,321
This vibe you mentioned -
is it still there?

335
00:18:12,441 --> 00:18:14,561
Yeah. I can't...

336
00:18:14,681 --> 00:18:16,721
It's like it won't let me
think.

337
00:18:16,841 --> 00:18:18,921
I need to get
out of this house.

338
00:18:28,041 --> 00:18:31,081
Easier said than done,
apparently.

339
00:18:31,201 --> 00:18:33,281
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

340
00:18:33,401 --> 00:18:36,761
- Oh... How many times now?
- RYAN: Seven?

341
00:18:36,881 --> 00:18:39,961
Mrs Doctor said the house
was evil. She must be right.

342
00:18:40,081 --> 00:18:42,001
It's turning against us.

343
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:44,321
A house can't do that.

344
00:18:44,441 --> 00:18:46,881
Even an evil one.

345
00:18:52,601 --> 00:18:55,441
Oh, don't worry. We're great at
sorting things out like this.

346
00:18:55,561 --> 00:18:57,041
There's always
an explanation...

347
00:18:57,161 --> 00:18:58,881
Oh, it touched me!
Ghost! Ghost.

348
00:18:59,001 --> 00:19:00,441
It definitely touched me.

349
00:19:00,561 --> 00:19:03,401
Ryan, that was my elbow.

350
00:19:03,521 --> 00:19:05,321
I knew that.

351
00:19:05,441 --> 00:19:07,121
I totally knew that.

352
00:19:07,241 --> 00:19:09,201
(BABY CRIES)

353
00:19:10,601 --> 00:19:13,321
Please tell me
there's a real baby in here.

354
00:19:13,441 --> 00:19:16,281
My son - William.
I must get to him!

355
00:19:21,201 --> 00:19:22,401
(BOTH GASP)

356
00:19:23,841 --> 00:19:25,561
(CRYING CONTINUES)

357
00:19:48,281 --> 00:19:50,201
You're going nowhere, pal.

358
00:19:50,321 --> 00:19:53,401
You're staying right there.
I'm on guard.

359
00:19:53,521 --> 00:19:54,881
Oh...

360
00:19:55,001 --> 00:19:57,281
Hey! Poli?

361
00:19:58,481 --> 00:19:59,921
Poli? Hello?

362
00:20:01,041 --> 00:20:02,041
Poli?

363
00:20:03,921 --> 00:20:05,921
Poli? Can you hear me, son?

364
00:20:07,481 --> 00:20:08,921
Can you hear me?

365
00:20:14,001 --> 00:20:16,121
(GROANS)

366
00:20:21,121 --> 00:20:23,241
The same chamber.

367
00:20:23,361 --> 00:20:24,721
Over and over.

368
00:20:26,081 --> 00:20:28,401
- How is it possible?
- It's not.

369
00:20:28,521 --> 00:20:30,321
- It's...
- Like a dream.

370
00:20:30,441 --> 00:20:31,881
Elise!

371
00:20:32,001 --> 00:20:33,681
Can you hear me?

372
00:20:34,921 --> 00:20:36,321
Do you have William?

373
00:20:36,441 --> 00:20:38,401
YAZ: He'll be OK.

374
00:20:38,521 --> 00:20:41,121
He probably just cried himself
out and fell asleep.

375
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:44,281
Doc! Poli! Doc! Doc!

376
00:20:46,721 --> 00:20:48,441
(GRAHAM GASPS)

377
00:20:49,921 --> 00:20:51,961
There's something
seriously wrong with this gaff.

378
00:20:52,081 --> 00:20:54,201
Is anyone else trapped?

379
00:20:54,321 --> 00:20:58,041
Yeah. And I think I'm seeing
dead people.

380
00:20:58,161 --> 00:21:00,761
(WIND WHISTLES)

381
00:21:04,041 --> 00:21:06,121
- Perfect...
- RYAN: We're the same!

382
00:21:06,241 --> 00:21:07,681
I totally saw a ghost.

383
00:21:07,801 --> 00:21:10,001
- We're stuck on the stairs!
- Please!

384
00:21:10,121 --> 00:21:13,921
How do we move upwards?
I need to check my son is well.

385
00:21:14,041 --> 00:21:17,641
Working on it!
Head's a bit fuzzy.

386
00:21:17,761 --> 00:21:20,321
Normal service will resume
shortly.

387
00:21:20,441 --> 00:21:22,801
- And ghosts don't exist.
- Of course not!

388
00:21:22,921 --> 00:21:26,001
You two just need a spray tan
and a kip, eh?

389
00:21:26,121 --> 00:21:27,081
Graham, what sort of

390
00:21:27,201 --> 00:21:28,681
dead people, exactly?

391
00:21:28,801 --> 00:21:31,961
Oh... How can I hear
your voice, Doc?

392
00:21:32,081 --> 00:21:34,361
(MUFFLED) I'm using
the fireplace chimney.

393
00:21:34,481 --> 00:21:35,881
Doc?

394
00:21:36,001 --> 00:21:37,321
Graham?

395
00:21:38,601 --> 00:21:39,681
Graham?

396
00:21:39,801 --> 00:21:41,241
They've gone now.

397
00:21:41,361 --> 00:21:42,521
And...

398
00:21:43,681 --> 00:21:44,841
...so's Polidori.

399
00:21:44,961 --> 00:21:47,361
- I've lost him.
- You had one job!

400
00:21:47,481 --> 00:21:48,681
Yeah, made more challenging

401
00:21:48,801 --> 00:21:50,841
by his ability to walk
through walls!

402
00:21:50,961 --> 00:21:51,801
Through?

403
00:21:51,921 --> 00:21:53,521
He just turned sort of zombie

404
00:21:53,641 --> 00:21:55,201
- and went into one.
- What do you speak of?

405
00:21:55,321 --> 00:21:56,361
What is a zombie?

406
00:21:56,481 --> 00:21:57,761
Mrs Doctor?

407
00:21:57,881 --> 00:21:59,801
Kind of a dead person walking,
but it won't be that.

408
00:21:59,921 --> 00:22:01,561
- Mrs Doctor?
- How do you know?

409
00:22:01,681 --> 00:22:03,601
Because Polidori isn't dead,
for a kick-off.

410
00:22:06,081 --> 00:22:08,441
- Mrs Doctor!
- Really, just Doctor is fine.

411
00:22:08,561 --> 00:22:09,681
Polidori!

412
00:22:09,801 --> 00:22:12,801
(GASPS) He emerged
from the wall like a phantom.

413
00:22:14,161 --> 00:22:16,041
Be gone, demon!

414
00:22:19,441 --> 00:22:22,041
Pulse - check.

415
00:22:22,161 --> 00:22:25,281
Breathing - check.

416
00:22:25,401 --> 00:22:29,361
May I just say, you are
quite lovely in a crisis.

417
00:22:29,481 --> 00:22:31,081
No, you may not!

418
00:22:32,641 --> 00:22:36,841
The lights are on.
He's gone on a mini-break.

419
00:22:36,961 --> 00:22:38,081
Possessed?

420
00:22:38,201 --> 00:22:40,761
Or asleep?
He walks in his sleep.

421
00:22:40,881 --> 00:22:42,801
One does not sleepwalk
through walls.

422
00:22:42,921 --> 00:22:45,321
Not just through - up.

423
00:22:45,441 --> 00:22:47,801
He was downstairs a second ago.

424
00:22:47,921 --> 00:22:49,161
What you said before...

425
00:22:49,281 --> 00:22:51,401
- About being lovely?
- Back a bit!

426
00:22:51,521 --> 00:22:53,281
Er... Demon?

427
00:22:55,281 --> 00:22:57,121
It's like dreaming...

428
00:22:58,321 --> 00:23:00,721
...only we aren't...and he is.

429
00:23:02,401 --> 00:23:06,761
So he can't see the illusion.

430
00:23:10,441 --> 00:23:12,121
It's more than that.

431
00:23:12,241 --> 00:23:15,241
We're surrounded. Immersed.

432
00:23:15,361 --> 00:23:18,001
It's sort of like
a perception filter.

433
00:23:20,041 --> 00:23:22,001
Close your eyes.
Clear your mind.

434
00:23:22,121 --> 00:23:25,761
We're only experiencing
what it wants us to.

435
00:23:28,321 --> 00:23:30,641
I can feel it.

436
00:23:30,761 --> 00:23:32,681
She's right.

437
00:23:32,801 --> 00:23:36,521
Our minds are being deceived.

438
00:23:36,641 --> 00:23:38,961
Here is the door,

439
00:23:39,081 --> 00:23:41,641
hidden from our eyes.

440
00:23:43,841 --> 00:23:45,721
Elise?

441
00:23:45,841 --> 00:23:47,241
I'm coming for William.

442
00:23:49,201 --> 00:23:50,761
MARY: How are we here now?

443
00:23:50,881 --> 00:23:52,401
This is impossible.

444
00:23:53,641 --> 00:23:55,761
This should be William's room.

445
00:23:55,881 --> 00:23:57,961
This place keeps on changing,
like a puzzle.

446
00:23:58,081 --> 00:23:59,801
I don't get it.

447
00:23:59,921 --> 00:24:02,561
Why hide a house
inside a house?

448
00:24:11,121 --> 00:24:13,321
William! My darling!

449
00:24:14,601 --> 00:24:18,041
(SCREAMS)

450
00:24:21,961 --> 00:24:23,961
I suspect I must have missed
something.

451
00:24:26,001 --> 00:24:29,161
Yes, but you've shown us
how to get out of this room.

452
00:24:29,281 --> 00:24:30,681
POLIDORI:
This cannot be the hallway.

453
00:24:30,801 --> 00:24:32,441
We've not descended the stairs.

454
00:24:35,801 --> 00:24:38,401
BYRON: It is. But there
should be a door here.

455
00:24:38,521 --> 00:24:39,601
Please can we get out of here?

456
00:24:39,721 --> 00:24:42,321
In theory, yes.
We just have to tell ourselves

457
00:24:42,441 --> 00:24:45,401
that we can walk
through the door

458
00:24:45,521 --> 00:24:48,041
we know is right there...

459
00:24:50,321 --> 00:24:51,521
- (THUD)
- (GASPS)

460
00:24:51,641 --> 00:24:52,921
Ohh!

461
00:24:54,481 --> 00:24:58,801
My bones have never caused
such mischief before, I swear.

462
00:24:58,921 --> 00:25:02,761
The things we know - we can
move inside but not out.

463
00:25:02,881 --> 00:25:04,161
Dead things don't act dead.

464
00:25:04,281 --> 00:25:06,521
People vanish. Elise?

465
00:25:06,641 --> 00:25:07,721
My poor William.

466
00:25:07,841 --> 00:25:09,361
RYAN: There's no sign
of Fletcher either.

467
00:25:09,481 --> 00:25:12,161
Hey, maybe Shelley didn't turn
up because he couldn't get in.

468
00:25:13,401 --> 00:25:16,161
I've never believed in such
things, but could this be Hell?

469
00:25:16,281 --> 00:25:18,241
Could we be deceased?

470
00:25:18,361 --> 00:25:20,521
Nice blue-sky thinking, but no.

471
00:25:20,641 --> 00:25:22,961
This place keeps on folding in
on itself as well.

472
00:25:23,081 --> 00:25:24,761
Exactly.

473
00:25:25,841 --> 00:25:28,121
I think we're caught in
a security system. It's...

474
00:25:28,241 --> 00:25:31,641
It's turned the house into
a sort of giant panic room.

475
00:25:31,761 --> 00:25:33,881
In 18167

476
00:25:36,241 --> 00:25:38,161
The Year Without a Summer.

477
00:25:38,281 --> 00:25:41,601
They blamed it on volcanic ash
covering the sunlight.

478
00:25:41,721 --> 00:25:43,081
Weather went haywire.

479
00:25:43,201 --> 00:25:45,761
What if something came here
that wasn't supposed to

480
00:25:45,881 --> 00:25:47,441
and caused a major disturbance?

481
00:25:47,561 --> 00:25:48,561
Like what?

482
00:25:48,681 --> 00:25:49,801
That?

483
00:25:53,081 --> 00:25:56,401
That could be a solid option,
Mary, yes.

484
00:25:57,641 --> 00:25:59,241
MARY: What is it?

485
00:25:59,361 --> 00:26:00,921
I don't know.

486
00:26:01,041 --> 00:26:05,001
RYAN: It's sort of
just floating around.

487
00:26:05,121 --> 00:26:07,121
Like a death god
rising from Hades.

488
00:26:07,241 --> 00:26:08,641
Shelley's vision.

489
00:26:08,761 --> 00:26:10,241
But we're all having it.

490
00:26:10,361 --> 00:26:12,081
No. It's pushing through.

491
00:26:12,201 --> 00:26:13,641
That is what Shelley saw.

492
00:26:13,761 --> 00:26:16,681
It's not a vision.
It never was.

493
00:26:16,801 --> 00:26:18,401
It's a traveller...

494
00:26:18,521 --> 00:26:21,081
...moving through time.

495
00:26:28,721 --> 00:26:31,041
And he's trying to get in.

496
00:26:38,121 --> 00:26:39,441
Are you the guardian?

497
00:26:39,561 --> 00:26:42,321
Thatis a lone Cyberman.

498
00:26:42,441 --> 00:26:45,721
(DOCTOR GASPS)

499
00:26:47,681 --> 00:26:50,841
Jack's warning - beware of
the lone Cyberman. Don't let it

500
00:26:50,961 --> 00:26:52,441
- have what it wants.
- At all costs!

501
00:26:52,561 --> 00:26:54,961
Yes, thank you!
Barricade the door!

502
00:26:55,081 --> 00:26:58,561
May I ask, what is a Cyberman?

503
00:26:58,681 --> 00:27:00,201
Someone altered.

504
00:27:00,321 --> 00:27:04,321
Organs, flesh surgically
replaced with mechanical parts

505
00:27:04,441 --> 00:27:05,641
without consent.

506
00:27:05,761 --> 00:27:08,561
He drives them insane
so they alter the brain too,

507
00:27:08,681 --> 00:27:11,081
- switch off all emotion.
- Are you the guardian?

508
00:27:11,201 --> 00:27:13,401
Never seen one like him before.
He's different.

509
00:27:13,521 --> 00:27:14,681
(BANG ON DOOR)

510
00:27:14,801 --> 00:27:17,401
- Unfinished.
- Are you the guardian?

511
00:27:17,521 --> 00:27:19,241
- (BANG ON DOOR)
- Whatever he came for

512
00:27:19,361 --> 00:27:22,201
is hidden here.
It explains the security.

513
00:27:22,321 --> 00:27:24,601
- What's hidden?
- I've no idea,

514
00:27:24,721 --> 00:27:26,921
but I need to beat him to it.
Quick.

515
00:27:27,041 --> 00:27:29,321
(BLASTER FIRES THEN FADES)

516
00:27:32,361 --> 00:27:34,081
FLETCHER: Lord Byron?

517
00:27:37,841 --> 00:27:41,241
Doctor, what are you doing?
Where are you going?

518
00:27:41,361 --> 00:27:42,881
You're not leaving us?

519
00:27:43,001 --> 00:27:45,121
I have to find out
what he's looking for.

520
00:27:45,241 --> 00:27:46,201
Alone.

521
00:27:46,321 --> 00:27:48,761
You need backup.
All of us against one.

522
00:27:48,881 --> 00:27:51,521
One Cyberman,
but then thousands.

523
00:27:51,641 --> 00:27:56,641
Humans like all of you changed
into empty, soulless shells.

524
00:27:56,761 --> 00:28:00,121
No feeling, no control,
no way back.

525
00:28:00,241 --> 00:28:02,881
I will not lose anyone else
to that!

526
00:28:03,001 --> 00:28:05,041
Do not follow me.

527
00:28:08,841 --> 00:28:10,561
Lord Byron?

528
00:28:10,681 --> 00:28:12,841
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

529
00:28:12,961 --> 00:28:15,001
Is that you?

530
00:28:16,481 --> 00:28:18,881
I fear I've lost my faculties
entirely.

531
00:28:19,001 --> 00:28:21,161
(GASPS)

532
00:28:21,281 --> 00:28:22,921
Are you the guardian?

533
00:28:23,041 --> 00:28:24,481
No, sir.

534
00:28:24,601 --> 00:28:26,841
I am the valet.

535
00:28:27,841 --> 00:28:29,481
(GROANS)

536
00:28:29,601 --> 00:28:31,881
(BABY CRIES)

537
00:28:45,641 --> 00:28:47,681
(BABY CRIES SOFTLY)

538
00:29:02,561 --> 00:29:04,641
(PRAYS SOFTLY IN FRENCH)

539
00:29:04,761 --> 00:29:06,921
(BABY CRIES)

540
00:29:07,041 --> 00:29:09,041
(CRYING INTENSIFIES)

541
00:29:09,161 --> 00:29:10,841
(GASPS)

542
00:29:10,961 --> 00:29:12,921
(PRAYING CONTINUES)

543
00:29:16,161 --> 00:29:17,521
(ELISE SCREAMS)

544
00:29:17,641 --> 00:29:19,641
(SCREAMING STOPS ABRUPTLY)

545
00:29:19,761 --> 00:29:21,521
(BABY CRIES SOFTLY)

546
00:29:23,961 --> 00:29:25,601
(CRYING STOPS)

547
00:29:37,721 --> 00:29:40,161
Don't be afraid, little one.

548
00:29:41,281 --> 00:29:42,681
You will be like us.

549
00:29:45,561 --> 00:29:46,921
MARY: What if it finds William?

550
00:29:47,041 --> 00:29:48,281
We need to find the child.

551
00:29:48,401 --> 00:29:51,401
- And a way out.
- We are not safe here.

552
00:29:51,521 --> 00:29:53,241
He could pass through a wall
at any moment.

553
00:29:53,361 --> 00:29:54,881
The Doctor told us to wait.

554
00:29:55,001 --> 00:29:58,921
Technically, she only told us
not to follow her.

555
00:30:01,201 --> 00:30:02,401
Let's split up.

556
00:30:09,281 --> 00:30:11,801
Tell me what you're after.
I might be able to help.

557
00:30:13,921 --> 00:30:15,681
Well, it was never going to be
under there...

558
00:30:15,801 --> 00:30:18,721
...unless you don't actually
know what it looks like.

559
00:30:18,841 --> 00:30:19,921
Funny...

560
00:30:21,081 --> 00:30:23,321
This dark age is surprising.

561
00:30:23,441 --> 00:30:26,081
You're not as primitive
as I expected.

562
00:30:26,201 --> 00:30:28,521
You're not as cyborg-y
as I expected.

563
00:30:33,201 --> 00:30:35,121
You have met my kind before?

564
00:30:36,681 --> 00:30:39,401
- You could say that.
- You appear courageous,

565
00:30:39,521 --> 00:30:43,681
but your vital signs betray
a heightened state of anxiety.

566
00:30:43,801 --> 00:30:47,121
Or as I like to call it,
Tuesday. Interesting look.

567
00:30:47,241 --> 00:30:49,921
What happened? They get bored
halfway through, or something?

568
00:30:50,041 --> 00:30:52,881
I am complete enough
to serve my purpose.

569
00:30:53,001 --> 00:30:55,241
(BLASTER FIRES THEN FADES)

570
00:30:56,401 --> 00:30:57,681
Oh.

571
00:30:57,801 --> 00:30:59,561
Bit embarrassing.

572
00:30:59,681 --> 00:31:02,761
Time hop took a lot of juice.
Now you're fresh out.

573
00:31:02,881 --> 00:31:05,361
You irritate me.

574
00:31:05,481 --> 00:31:08,441
How very human.
Still feel things, then?

575
00:31:08,561 --> 00:31:09,481
No inhibitor yet.

576
00:31:09,601 --> 00:31:11,681
I do not need to be stabilised!

577
00:31:11,801 --> 00:31:15,681
OK. Here's the thing. There's a
chance I might be the guardian,

578
00:31:15,801 --> 00:31:17,641
only I don't know what it is
I'm supposed to be guarding.

579
00:31:17,761 --> 00:31:19,041
This isn't my time either.

580
00:31:19,161 --> 00:31:21,361
Maybe we're supposed to work
together.

581
00:31:21,481 --> 00:31:23,841
- Together?
- Anything's possible.

582
00:31:26,041 --> 00:31:27,721
The house still shifts.

583
00:31:32,561 --> 00:31:35,401
- Whose room is this?
- No-one's.

584
00:31:35,521 --> 00:31:36,921
I thought it was empty.

585
00:31:37,041 --> 00:31:39,521
YAZ: But the writing on the
walls and all of these papers?

586
00:31:39,641 --> 00:31:42,801
The writing... It's Shelley's.

587
00:31:43,841 --> 00:31:45,721
(DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

588
00:31:48,561 --> 00:31:49,801
The cellar.

589
00:31:49,921 --> 00:31:51,121
We'll give it a miss, eh?

590
00:31:51,241 --> 00:31:53,761
Could the coal hatch be
a means of escape?

591
00:31:53,881 --> 00:31:55,521
We should try everywhere.

592
00:31:55,641 --> 00:31:57,921
Is it too late to choose
another group?

593
00:31:58,041 --> 00:32:00,681
(WIND WHISTLES)

594
00:32:10,521 --> 00:32:13,001
Ooh! You ever considered
breath mints?

595
00:32:13,121 --> 00:32:15,121
Recharging? Not good.

596
00:32:17,561 --> 00:32:19,881
Figuring out how to
manipulate the elements

597
00:32:20,001 --> 00:32:23,041
and creating
an extremely sophisticated

598
00:32:23,161 --> 00:32:26,761
and probably unlimited
external power source.

599
00:32:33,521 --> 00:32:35,561
That's better!

600
00:32:39,801 --> 00:32:42,161
POLIDORI:
The coal hatch has gone.

601
00:32:45,281 --> 00:32:46,841
There's no way out.

602
00:32:52,721 --> 00:32:54,801
Claire, you OK?

603
00:32:54,921 --> 00:32:56,361
Miss Clairmont?

604
00:32:56,481 --> 00:33:00,001
(SHAKILY) There's something
down here with us.

605
00:33:00,121 --> 00:33:02,401
I can read the energy field
now.

606
00:33:04,241 --> 00:33:06,961
You are not the guardian.

607
00:33:07,081 --> 00:33:10,001
The Cyberium has selected
another as host too.

608
00:33:10,121 --> 00:33:12,041
What's a Cyberium?

609
00:33:12,161 --> 00:33:15,521
I'll find it and remove it.

610
00:33:15,641 --> 00:33:16,881
What are we talking here?

611
00:33:17,001 --> 00:33:20,561
A life form?
A weapon of some kind?

612
00:33:20,681 --> 00:33:21,921
Both...

613
00:33:24,841 --> 00:33:26,681
What's happening to you?

614
00:33:30,761 --> 00:33:34,161
There's not one atom
of yon earth...

615
00:33:36,841 --> 00:33:40,361
...but once was living man.

616
00:33:43,881 --> 00:33:45,921
The sword that stabs
his peace...

617
00:33:46,041 --> 00:33:47,481
CYBERMAN AND MARY:
...He cherisheth

618
00:33:47,601 --> 00:33:50,081
The snakes that gnaw his heart

619
00:33:50,201 --> 00:33:52,761
And he raises up the tyrant
Whose delight...

620
00:33:54,441 --> 00:33:56,001
CYBERMAN: ...is in woe.

621
00:33:56,121 --> 00:33:57,521
(GASPS)

622
00:33:57,641 --> 00:33:59,201
Shelley's words.

623
00:33:59,321 --> 00:34:01,361
How does it know them?

624
00:34:01,481 --> 00:34:04,601
Something crept in front of me.
I heard its vile breath.

625
00:34:04,721 --> 00:34:06,281
Listen...

626
00:34:06,401 --> 00:34:08,241
(WIND WHISTLES)

627
00:34:22,361 --> 00:34:25,121
I'm sorry,
but I tried to hide it.

628
00:34:25,241 --> 00:34:27,721
I have to keep him out.

629
00:34:27,841 --> 00:34:29,641
Who are you?

630
00:34:29,761 --> 00:34:31,921
I'm the guardian.

631
00:34:33,401 --> 00:34:34,361
I am...

632
00:34:34,481 --> 00:34:37,241
SHELLEY AND CYBERMAN:
...Percy Bysshe Shelley.

633
00:34:37,361 --> 00:34:41,161
He is whom I seek.

634
00:34:41,281 --> 00:34:45,281
But he is fortified against me!

635
00:34:45,401 --> 00:34:48,401
OK. Good to know.
So I vote we split up

636
00:34:48,521 --> 00:34:51,281
and continue the search.
You go this way, and I'll go...

637
00:35:04,241 --> 00:35:08,081
- YAZ: Doctor, you're here!
- Come on, then.

638
00:35:08,201 --> 00:35:10,681
Oh... William!

639
00:35:16,521 --> 00:35:20,041
Dear Fletcher, no.
It cannot be.

640
00:35:22,721 --> 00:35:24,601
Mr O'Brien needs you
in the cellar at once.

641
00:35:24,721 --> 00:35:26,801
We found Shelley.

642
00:35:26,921 --> 00:35:29,801
All of you,
find somewhere to hide.

643
00:35:29,921 --> 00:35:31,281
- But I...
- Do you want to listen,

644
00:35:31,401 --> 00:35:32,801
or do you want to end up
like them?

645
00:35:32,921 --> 00:35:35,441
None of this is
supposed to happen.

646
00:35:35,561 --> 00:35:37,441
They weren't supposed to die,
neither are you,

647
00:35:37,561 --> 00:35:39,801
so, please, let's not unravel
anything else.

648
00:35:39,921 --> 00:35:42,161
Hide, and stay there.

649
00:35:42,281 --> 00:35:44,641
History is vulnerable tonight.

650
00:35:44,761 --> 00:35:46,641
I mean it.

651
00:35:46,761 --> 00:35:47,761
Now go on.

652
00:35:51,401 --> 00:35:54,081
You're going to take William
for me.

653
00:35:54,201 --> 00:35:55,721
(WILLIAM GURGLES)

654
00:35:56,721 --> 00:35:58,561
Guard him well.

655
00:35:58,681 --> 00:36:00,961
Stay safe.

656
00:36:01,081 --> 00:36:02,761
I need to see Percy.

657
00:36:05,401 --> 00:36:07,001
- (SONIC BUZZES)
- Shelley in a cellar,

658
00:36:07,121 --> 00:36:10,801
hidden away, cloaked -
too big to register.

659
00:36:10,921 --> 00:36:12,681
That's why my readings
have been off.

660
00:36:12,801 --> 00:36:15,201
It's something called
a Cyberium.

661
00:36:16,321 --> 00:36:18,481
I'm trying to protect it.

662
00:36:20,921 --> 00:36:23,321
- (DOCTOR GASPS)
- SHELLEY: Be gone, invader!

663
00:36:32,201 --> 00:36:33,521
(EXHALES)

664
00:36:33,641 --> 00:36:35,081
(ROARS)

665
00:36:35,201 --> 00:36:38,361
- (ROAR ECHOES)
- Who moved him?

666
00:36:38,481 --> 00:36:40,921
Is it you? Changing the house?

667
00:36:41,041 --> 00:36:44,041
Some, but not all.

668
00:36:44,161 --> 00:36:45,681
It has its own room.

669
00:36:45,801 --> 00:36:48,761
- Mary!
- I cannot hide.

670
00:36:48,881 --> 00:36:51,441
Not while he suffers.

671
00:36:53,601 --> 00:36:55,801
Show me.

672
00:36:55,921 --> 00:36:57,681
What happened to you?

673
00:37:02,041 --> 00:37:04,561
I was out walking alone.

674
00:37:04,681 --> 00:37:06,321
There was a glimmer
in the lake.

675
00:37:07,361 --> 00:37:08,961
Exquisite.

676
00:37:09,081 --> 00:37:10,681
Alive.

677
00:37:10,801 --> 00:37:16,121
Like quicksilver. I fished it
out to study it more closely.

678
00:37:17,921 --> 00:37:21,721
But then it took root
within me.

679
00:37:23,241 --> 00:37:25,201
(CRACKLING)

680
00:37:31,281 --> 00:37:33,161
(GASPS)

681
00:37:33,281 --> 00:37:35,361
I returned...

682
00:37:35,481 --> 00:37:36,401
Hello!

683
00:37:36,521 --> 00:37:37,521
I was changed.

684
00:37:37,641 --> 00:37:38,841
(GROANS)

685
00:37:42,561 --> 00:37:44,201
No-one could see me.

686
00:37:44,321 --> 00:37:48,081
It hid itself in me, and hid me
within the villa.

687
00:37:48,201 --> 00:37:51,081
DOCTOR: And when it thought
it might be discovered,

688
00:37:51,201 --> 00:37:53,001
it manipulated
all of our perceptions.

689
00:37:53,121 --> 00:37:55,121
SHELLEY: Since the quicksilver
has taken hold of me,

690
00:37:55,241 --> 00:37:57,721
I see symbols.
Symbols and numbers.

691
00:37:57,841 --> 00:37:59,321
They will not leave my head,

692
00:37:59,441 --> 00:38:01,201
no matter how much
I transcribe them.

693
00:38:01,321 --> 00:38:03,401
YAZ: The symbols were
all over his room.

694
00:38:03,521 --> 00:38:05,401
All over the walls.

695
00:38:05,521 --> 00:38:08,681
The house was like
shifting sands.

696
00:38:10,441 --> 00:38:13,961
I sought solitude here,
in the dark.

697
00:38:14,081 --> 00:38:16,361
- What happened to him?
- I'm going with...

698
00:38:16,481 --> 00:38:19,801
- ...alien parasite.
- Cyber technology.

699
00:38:19,921 --> 00:38:21,681
The knowledge of the whole
cyber race and Al

700
00:38:21,801 --> 00:38:23,401
from the future,

701
00:38:23,521 --> 00:38:27,841
containing the knowledge and
future history of all Cybermen.

702
00:38:27,961 --> 00:38:29,961
SHELLEY: They scorched
and split the sky.

703
00:38:30,081 --> 00:38:32,081
Built the army of all armies.

704
00:38:32,201 --> 00:38:36,881
Left behind only pain, rage,
fear and death.

705
00:38:37,001 --> 00:38:38,761
MARY: How has he seen all this?

706
00:38:38,881 --> 00:38:40,441
The Cyberium is burning through
his mind.

707
00:38:40,561 --> 00:38:42,921
It'll destroy him
if it stays in him much longer.

708
00:38:43,041 --> 00:38:46,361
An epic battle. The Cyberium
at the heart of it,

709
00:38:46,481 --> 00:38:49,961
controlling data, strategy,
decision-making.

710
00:38:50,081 --> 00:38:51,201
Clever!

711
00:38:51,321 --> 00:38:53,681
Very clever. Someone took it
from the Cybermen,

712
00:38:53,801 --> 00:38:54,921
sent it back through time here

713
00:38:55,041 --> 00:38:57,721
in an attempt to change
the future. (GASPS)

714
00:38:57,841 --> 00:39:01,361
In an attempt to protect it
from that.

715
00:39:01,481 --> 00:39:04,481
I can't keep him away
much longer.

716
00:39:05,761 --> 00:39:07,521
Then don't.

717
00:39:09,001 --> 00:39:10,881
) - Doc!
Stop fighting

718
00:39:11,001 --> 00:39:12,681
- It's OK.
- Jack's warning!

719
00:39:12,801 --> 00:39:14,521
Jack isn't here now,
stuck in a house with that.

720
00:39:14,641 --> 00:39:16,281
Exactly. You didn't want us
near it a minute ago.

721
00:39:16,401 --> 00:39:17,801
I've just been inside
his brain.

722
00:39:17,921 --> 00:39:20,241
There's a supercomputer
fused to a cerebral cortex.

723
00:39:20,361 --> 00:39:23,281
He's the only one who knows
how to get that out!

724
00:39:23,401 --> 00:39:24,521
Don't let the Cyberman have
what it wants.

725
00:39:24,641 --> 00:39:28,081
I know, because armies will
rise and billions will die.

726
00:39:28,201 --> 00:39:30,161
Shelley's going to die
if that stuff stays inside him.

727
00:39:30,281 --> 00:39:32,241
Shelley's only one life
against all those others.

728
00:39:34,001 --> 00:39:36,201
What are you saying?

729
00:39:36,321 --> 00:39:39,121
How can you condemn him
to death like that?

730
00:39:40,561 --> 00:39:41,921
But is he, Ryan?

731
00:39:42,041 --> 00:39:45,801
His thoughts, his words
inspire and influence thousands

732
00:39:45,921 --> 00:39:48,241
for centuries. If he dies now,

733
00:39:48,361 --> 00:39:51,081
who knows what damage that will
have on future history?

734
00:39:53,041 --> 00:39:55,281
Words matter!

735
00:39:57,281 --> 00:40:02,481
One death, one ripple, and
history will change in a blink.

736
00:40:02,601 --> 00:40:04,561
The future will not be
the world you know.

737
00:40:04,681 --> 00:40:07,561
The world you came from,
the world you were created in

738
00:40:07,681 --> 00:40:10,121
won't exist,
so neither will you.

739
00:40:10,241 --> 00:40:14,401
It's not just his life
at stake. It's yours.

740
00:40:14,521 --> 00:40:16,841
You want to sacrifice yourself
for this?

741
00:40:16,961 --> 00:40:18,761
You want me to sacrifice you?

742
00:40:18,881 --> 00:40:20,601
You want to call it? Do it now.

743
00:40:20,721 --> 00:40:22,001
All of you.

744
00:40:29,361 --> 00:40:33,961
Yeah. Cos sometimes
this team structure isn't flat.

745
00:40:34,081 --> 00:40:36,801
It's mountainous,
with me at the summit

746
00:40:36,921 --> 00:40:39,281
in the stratosphere. Alone.

747
00:40:39,401 --> 00:40:41,361
Left to choose.

748
00:40:42,881 --> 00:40:45,401
Save the poet,
save the universe.

749
00:40:47,321 --> 00:40:49,921
Watch people burn now
or tomorrow.

750
00:40:50,041 --> 00:40:52,801
Sometimes, even I can't win.

751
00:40:58,681 --> 00:41:00,161
Please...

752
00:41:00,281 --> 00:41:02,001
Help me.

753
00:41:05,881 --> 00:41:07,081
(GASPS)

754
00:41:07,201 --> 00:41:08,761
Release what you hold.

755
00:41:08,881 --> 00:41:11,441
- How?
- Release it!

756
00:41:11,561 --> 00:41:12,521
GRAHAM: He doesn't know
what that means!

757
00:41:12,641 --> 00:41:13,961
You've got to tell him
what he's got to do!

758
00:41:14,081 --> 00:41:16,241
I am addressing the Cyberium.

759
00:41:16,361 --> 00:41:19,921
It must execute the host
to be extracted.

760
00:41:20,041 --> 00:41:21,281
It's not obeying you.

761
00:41:21,401 --> 00:41:22,761
Hmm.

762
00:41:22,881 --> 00:41:26,441
Then I shall execute the host.

763
00:41:26,561 --> 00:41:29,081
What is your name, sir?

764
00:41:29,201 --> 00:41:31,401
Mary, this is not a good time
to talk.

765
00:41:31,521 --> 00:41:34,481
Or names. Are you several men?

766
00:41:34,601 --> 00:41:36,521
A composite of parts.

767
00:41:36,641 --> 00:41:39,841
I am better than men!

768
00:41:39,961 --> 00:41:42,201
Yet I still see a soul
in there.

769
00:41:42,321 --> 00:41:43,841
(CHUCKLES)

770
00:41:43,961 --> 00:41:47,121
What do you think you see,
child?

771
00:41:47,241 --> 00:41:51,041
I see the man
who spared my son.

772
00:41:56,441 --> 00:41:58,881
Were you a father? Before?

773
00:42:00,441 --> 00:42:02,041
I was.

774
00:42:03,361 --> 00:42:05,601
You didn't want to be this way.

775
00:42:05,721 --> 00:42:08,681
They hurt you,
this modern Prometheus.

776
00:42:10,361 --> 00:42:12,761
You loved once.

777
00:42:12,881 --> 00:42:14,761
(WHIRRING)

778
00:42:14,881 --> 00:42:17,001
And were loved in return.

779
00:42:18,361 --> 00:42:19,961
You do not wish to kill.

780
00:42:27,321 --> 00:42:31,601
My name was Ashad.

781
00:42:35,001 --> 00:42:38,201
I did spare your son...

782
00:42:38,321 --> 00:42:39,801
(WHIRRING)

783
00:42:39,921 --> 00:42:42,761
...because he's a useless runt,

784
00:42:42,881 --> 00:42:45,281
sickly and weak.

785
00:42:45,401 --> 00:42:47,161
And I did have children.

786
00:42:47,281 --> 00:42:51,201
I slit their throats when
they joined the resistance.

787
00:42:51,321 --> 00:42:55,001
- (SHRIEKS)
- In death we are transformed,

788
00:42:55,121 --> 00:42:59,161
improved, updated,
as you will learn!

789
00:42:59,281 --> 00:43:01,161
Transformed in death.

790
00:43:01,281 --> 00:43:04,521
I'm sorry, Percy Shelley.
So very sorry.

791
00:43:07,161 --> 00:43:09,281
MARY: Mrs Doctor, what are you
doing to him?

792
00:43:11,921 --> 00:43:12,761
Doctor...

793
00:43:17,601 --> 00:43:20,881
YAZ: The Cyberium!
It's leaving his body!

794
00:43:23,801 --> 00:43:25,081
GRAHAM: What just happened?

795
00:43:25,201 --> 00:43:27,681
- YAZ: How are we back here?
- He's reset the house.

796
00:43:27,801 --> 00:43:29,721
Shelley needs help!

797
00:43:29,841 --> 00:43:31,521
I think I've freed him
from the Cyberium!

798
00:43:31,641 --> 00:43:34,201
At what cost?

799
00:43:37,121 --> 00:43:39,441
ASHAD: No!

800
00:43:39,561 --> 00:43:41,881
And it chooses me.

801
00:43:42,001 --> 00:43:43,721
Interesting.

802
00:43:43,841 --> 00:43:45,561
Time Lord magnetism.

803
00:43:45,681 --> 00:43:47,481
Looks like
I'm the true guardian.

804
00:43:48,561 --> 00:43:50,121
(GASPS)

805
00:43:50,241 --> 00:43:54,121
Surrender it
or I will execute you.

806
00:43:54,241 --> 00:43:56,521
I'd be very careful
with those execution threats.

807
00:43:56,641 --> 00:43:59,001
I can feel it already,
fusing to me.

808
00:43:59,121 --> 00:44:00,641
It feels very at home.

809
00:44:00,761 --> 00:44:02,481
Recognising great
host material.

810
00:44:02,601 --> 00:44:03,761
Not to big myself up,

811
00:44:03,881 --> 00:44:05,881
but I don't think it'll vacate
me without a fight.

812
00:44:06,001 --> 00:44:07,601
(WHIRRING)

813
00:44:07,721 --> 00:44:10,881
- (STORM INTENSIFIES)
- (ASHAD ROARS)

814
00:44:14,081 --> 00:44:16,041
- What are you doing?
- Transmitting.

815
00:44:16,161 --> 00:44:19,001
My ship will lock on
to my signal.

816
00:44:19,121 --> 00:44:21,321
It will tear this reality,

817
00:44:21,441 --> 00:44:25,601
and this planet will remain
only in shreds!

818
00:44:25,721 --> 00:44:27,601
This world doesn't end in 1816.

819
00:44:27,721 --> 00:44:29,281
It can't.

820
00:44:29,401 --> 00:44:30,401
It will.

821
00:44:30,521 --> 00:44:32,881
He's bluffing.
Don't listen to him.

822
00:44:33,001 --> 00:44:37,081
But I can't be sure.
I can't risk this planet!

823
00:44:37,201 --> 00:44:38,121
I can't win!

824
00:44:38,241 --> 00:44:41,121
We are inevitable.

825
00:44:44,361 --> 00:44:45,721
Yes.

826
00:44:46,841 --> 00:44:48,801
You are.

827
00:44:51,841 --> 00:44:53,281
What are you doing?

828
00:44:53,401 --> 00:44:54,881
Giving it what it wants.

829
00:45:01,801 --> 00:45:03,281
(BIRDSONG)

830
00:45:03,401 --> 00:45:05,481
(ALL GASP)

831
00:45:09,921 --> 00:45:11,881
What did you do to Shelley?

832
00:45:12,001 --> 00:45:13,721
Old Time Lord trick.
Not a nice one.

833
00:45:13,841 --> 00:45:15,841
Pushed his mind
to his future death,

834
00:45:15,961 --> 00:45:18,041
tricked the Cyberium
into letting go,

835
00:45:18,161 --> 00:45:20,681
hoped his body would survive
the trauma. I'm sorry.

836
00:45:20,801 --> 00:45:22,041
I hope you can forgive me.

837
00:45:22,161 --> 00:45:25,161
You saved Shelley, but what
does that mean for the future?

838
00:45:25,281 --> 00:45:26,921
It means I've put it
in the gravest danger.

839
00:45:27,041 --> 00:45:28,001
Please tell me

840
00:45:28,121 --> 00:45:29,361
- that was part of the plan.
- Yes.

841
00:45:29,481 --> 00:45:32,121
A last-minute,
imperfect, all-I've-got plan.

842
00:45:32,241 --> 00:45:34,161
Saving Shelley was step one.

843
00:45:34,281 --> 00:45:35,481
What's step two?

844
00:45:35,601 --> 00:45:37,601
Fix the mess
I created in step one.

845
00:45:42,121 --> 00:45:44,321
Go to the future, find him

846
00:45:44,441 --> 00:45:48,241
and stop him from rebuilding
the Cyber Army.

847
00:45:48,361 --> 00:45:51,601
Shelley, can you give Yaz
those symbols and numbers?

848
00:45:51,721 --> 00:45:53,401
We're going to need them.

849
00:45:58,521 --> 00:46:00,561
POLIDORI: Well, that was
quite the evening.

850
00:46:00,681 --> 00:46:02,561
Indeed.

851
00:46:04,361 --> 00:46:06,961
Perhaps Miss Clairmont
would care to retire?

852
00:46:08,801 --> 00:46:11,321
A lie-down could prove
restorative.

853
00:46:12,841 --> 00:46:16,001
You pursued Mrs Doctor without
a care for my presence...

854
00:46:17,601 --> 00:46:19,561
...belittled my thoughts
and opinions...

855
00:46:20,721 --> 00:46:24,401
...and then proceeded to use
my person as a human shield.

856
00:46:24,521 --> 00:46:26,361
And...?

857
00:46:27,721 --> 00:46:29,641
And the spell is broken,

858
00:46:29,761 --> 00:46:31,001
my lord.

859
00:46:43,961 --> 00:46:45,441
You have returned me to life,

860
00:46:45,561 --> 00:46:48,401
although I feel as though
I have none of it left to live.

861
00:46:48,521 --> 00:46:51,401
Sorry about the sneak peek.

862
00:46:51,521 --> 00:46:53,321
Every moment will be precious.

863
00:46:55,161 --> 00:46:56,441
How can we repay you?

864
00:46:56,561 --> 00:46:57,961
Just don't lose hope.

865
00:46:58,081 --> 00:47:00,881
Yeah. Keep doing
that writing thing.

866
00:47:01,001 --> 00:47:02,041
If you like.

867
00:47:08,761 --> 00:47:11,241
So, if all the weirdness was
the Cyberium, you know,

868
00:47:11,361 --> 00:47:13,481
the bones and Shelley
floating about and all that,

869
00:47:13,601 --> 00:47:15,881
why would it reanimate
a couple of stiffs

870
00:47:16,001 --> 00:47:17,641
just to bring me a sarnie?

871
00:47:17,761 --> 00:47:20,121
You know, the maid
and the creepy little kid?

872
00:47:20,241 --> 00:47:21,881
Er...no.

873
00:47:23,361 --> 00:47:25,281
We thought you saw Shelley,
like we did.

874
00:47:25,401 --> 00:47:29,161
Oh, come on! Beady eyes?
Made the room go all arctic?

875
00:47:29,281 --> 00:47:31,761
- Where do them two fit in?
- I'm not sure they did.

876
00:47:31,881 --> 00:47:32,801
No, come on, Doc.

877
00:47:32,921 --> 00:47:34,401
This is where you jump in
with a rational explanation.

878
00:47:34,521 --> 00:47:35,721
I mean, ghosts don't exist,
right?

879
00:47:35,841 --> 00:47:38,161
- Unless they do.
- What?!

880
00:47:39,921 --> 00:47:41,401
Inside, you three.

881
00:47:41,521 --> 00:47:42,681
We need to talk.

882
00:47:44,361 --> 00:47:45,561
Listen...

883
00:47:45,681 --> 00:47:47,761
You don't need to come with me.

884
00:47:47,881 --> 00:47:50,761
Cyber war zones and people
don't mix.

885
00:47:50,881 --> 00:47:53,521
I'll drop you back in 2020.

886
00:47:53,641 --> 00:47:55,641
Or we can use
Shelley's numbers.

887
00:47:55,761 --> 00:47:57,121
Co-ordinates, right?

888
00:48:01,241 --> 00:48:04,161
Yeah. Wherever you think's
a good place to start.

889
00:48:04,281 --> 00:48:05,721
With step two.

890
00:48:07,041 --> 00:48:09,601
BYRON: The world was void

891
00:48:09,721 --> 00:48:11,681
The populous and the powerful
was a lump

892
00:48:11,801 --> 00:48:14,681
Seasonless, her bless, treeless

893
00:48:14,801 --> 00:48:17,081
Manless, lifeless

894
00:48:17,201 --> 00:48:18,881
A lump of death

895
00:48:19,001 --> 00:48:21,521
A chaos of hard clay

896
00:48:21,641 --> 00:48:25,761
Ships sailor less lay rotting
on the sea

897
00:48:25,881 --> 00:48:28,801
And their masts fell down
piecemeal

898
00:48:28,921 --> 00:48:30,281
As they dropped

899
00:48:30,401 --> 00:48:33,601
They slept on the abyss
without a surge

900
00:48:33,721 --> 00:48:35,721
The waves were dead

901
00:48:35,841 --> 00:48:38,121
The tides were in their grave

902
00:48:39,441 --> 00:48:41,041
The moon, their mistress

903
00:48:41,161 --> 00:48:43,401
Had expired before

904
00:48:43,521 --> 00:48:46,121
The winds withered
in the stagnant air

905
00:48:46,241 --> 00:48:47,441
And the clouds perished

906
00:48:49,761 --> 00:48:52,081
Darkness had no need of aid
from them

907
00:48:54,441 --> 00:48:56,241
She was the universe.

908
00:49:29,921 --> 00:49:32,441
DOCTOR: Any ideas
what we're walking into -

909
00:49:32,561 --> 00:49:35,001
this planet, this time period,

910
00:49:35,121 --> 00:49:36,881
in the very far future,

911
00:49:37,001 --> 00:49:39,881
immediate aftermath
of the Cyber Wars?

